defaultPrinciple 4- Authority to remedy injustice and require service improvementdefault&#xa0;defaultIf complaints cannot be addressed by the local provider, the public want to know that their complaint will
default be investigated by somebody
default with the authority to 
defaultput things right.  
defaultThe strength of an Ombudsman approach is the 
defaultauthority to
default remedy both the injustice caused to individuals by the actions of public services and to tackle the wider injustices that may occur by requiring service improvements. The current public service ombudsmen all have differ
defaulting
default powers to aid them in meeting these objectives
default.
default 
defaultClarification of enforcement powers could be achieved as follows: 
default&#xa0;defaultUnder the current system public bodies usually comply with ombudsmen recommendations.  The sovereignty of the legislature to make decisions concerning policy and the use of public money has
default however
default been maintained. 
defaultBoth LGO and PHSO report in excess of 99% compliance
default. As changes in service delivery bring more independent bodies into jurisdiction, for example all registered social care providers which have been in the jurisdiction of LGO since 2010, the Ombudsman must maintain appropriate authority to achieve compliance.  This would be strengthened by 
defaultdiscretion to seek judicial enforcement of recommendations. However, this power should be subject to an affirmative instrument before it comes into effect.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
defaultIn the regulatory landscape of public services, proper arrangements need to be in place to provide a route to redress for individual complaints or groups of complainants.  This is not the role of the regulator
defaulty
default body
default which has responsibility and authority to ensure systemic change in line with regulatory standards. The ombudsman will however consider compliance with regulatory standards in determining a complaint. The ombudsman and the regulator need to work together to share intelligence, learn from complaints and bring about improvement action.  The LGO works closely with appropriate regulators for social care and education to achieve this.   A duty on the ombudsman to refer concerns to the relevant regulator with a similar duty on the regulator to follow up would strengthen this relationship and provide further public assurance.
default&#xa0;
defaultPrinciple 5- Strong local complaint handling with independent oversightdefault&#xa0;defaultMembers of the public want their complaints resolved as quickly as possible by the body concerned.  Referral to the 
defaulto
defaultmbudsm
defaulta
defaultn 
defaultis a final stage and should only be necessary when local routes for redress have been exhausted. 
defaultThe ombudsman sits at the apex of the system, not only to provide independent and robust oversight when local complaints handling fails, but 
defaultalso to
default ensure that bodies take responsibility and accountability for their own performance and for resolving complaints. 
defaultThe role of the ombudsman must also be to 
defaultencourage robust
default and effective
default local complaint handling. 
default&#xa0;
defaultLGO has for nearly 40 years provided informal guidance, advice and training for local councils in support of local complaints handling.  
defaultIn his evidence to the Committee, the Scottish Public Services Ombudsman highlighted his work in setting common standards for complaints handling through a Complaints Standards Authority.
default A statutory duty for 
defaulta 
defaultPublic
default Services Ombudsman for England
default 
defaultwould be the appropriate way to formalise and strengthen this role.  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultIn the Scottish model, Audit Scotland has the role to audit compliance with the standards set by the Complaint Standards Authority. We consider that an arrangement of this nature helps to prevent confusion between the role of an ombudsman and the role of a regulator.
default We would recommend that a similar approach is taken in England with relevant regulators such as the National Audit Office and the Care Quality Commission being responsible for auditing compliance with complaint standards set by a Public Services Ombudsman for England.
default&#xa0;defaultPrinciple 6- Value for moneydefault&#xa0;defaultAn ombudsman service must be free of charge to the complainant. 
defaultAs with any publically funded service, a Public Service Ombudsman for England
default should provide value for money. 
defaultWhere a service is publically funded through taxation it follows that the relevant ombudsman scheme should also be publically funded.  However where bodies in jurisdiction are not publically funded 
defaultthey should not be funded by the tax payer.  
defaultAs is usually the case with ombudsman schemes serving the private sector, a 
defaultPublic Services Ombudsman for England should have powers to recover the costs of investigating complaints about non-public bodies from the providers themselves. This could be done by using 
defaulteither a sector wide levy, a case fee for each complaint handled about a provider or a combination of both.
default This would reduce the burden on the public purse and help to ensure that all providers are accountable.
